> The best value of an 009 is it only wastes $50 or so to get by until you
> find a better curved dizzy. This does not include the T-IV motor. It's
dead
> wrong and cannot in any way meet specs.
>
> I have verified curves on a number of 009's and have found in the cases
> where they were not worn they all hit within a degree or two of 25° total
> range. The 009 is shown by Bosch as a suitable replacement for some VW
> engines, but not the T-IV in any case.
>
> Standard procedure when first installing and running any new or used dizzy
> is verifying the curve with a tack and timing light. Plot the advance/rpm
> every 500 rpm up to total advance. Compare your curve with stock. If you
> are within the stock curve min-max area at all rpm's, you can use it and
> expect suitable function. If not, find a better fit ASAP.
>
